03977nam a22006495i 9780674056589DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740565897 a10.4159/97806740565892doi  a(DE-B1597)613920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQH378 7aSCI0270002bisacsh04a576.8/51 aKozo-Polyansky, Boris Mikhaylovich, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSymbiogenesis :bA New Principle of Evolution /cBoris Mikhaylovich Kozo-Polyansky, Lynn Margulis, Victor Fet. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe Importance of B. M. Kozo-Polyansky’s Work for Modern Science -- tIntroduction -- tNote to the Reader -- tKozo- Polyansky’s Life -- tAcknowledgments -- tOriginal Russian book title page -- tPreface -- tI Noncellular Organisms (Cytodes) and Bioblasts [Prokaryotes] -- tII The Cell and Its Organelles -- tIII Multicellular Organisms -- tIV The Philosophy of Symbiogenesis -- tV History of Symbiogenesis Theory -- tReferences to Kozo-Polyansky’s Text -- tKozo- Polyansky’s Taxa -- tEditors’ Commentary -- tCommentary References -- tModern Classification of Life -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMore than eighty years ago, before we knew much about the structure of cells, Russian botanist Boris Kozo-Polyansky brilliantly outlined the concept of symbiogenesis, the symbiotic origin of cells with nuclei. It was a half-century later, only when experimental approaches that Kozo-Polyansky lacked were applied to his hypotheses, that scientists began to accept his view that symbiogenesis could be united with Darwin's concept of natural selection to explain the evolution of life. After decades of neglect, ridicule, and intellectual abuse, Kozo-Polyansky's ideas are now endorsed by virtually all biologists. Kozo-Polyansky's seminal work is presented here for the first time in an outstanding annotated translation, updated with commentaries, references, and modern micrographs of symbiotic phenomena.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aSymbiogenesis. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh1 aFet, Victor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFet, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhakhina, Liya N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargulis, Lynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMargulis, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaven, Peter H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674056589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674056589/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK